>what story did you make, anon?
Broken Sanctuary, thanks for asking.

I think my favorite part about Flames and Flour is the tight, very straightforward world building that did not waste any time at all. Everything you needed to know was there and it left me wanting more all at once. My only complaint might be that the sous chef just kind of appeared when he talked to her while we got this paragraph about the kobolds, but I might have missed something somewhere. Even at that, I still followed along without further issue. Given how everything in the story, every name, had a purpose the little twist was something I should've seen coming but I was actually surprised by it and it was great. Then with the progression after the big event and the little back and forth with the green guy it really set that ending up. If this story stayed as a one-off it would be a little tragic, but the ending was perfect in my opinion. Much better than anything I've ever written. That was a fantastic read and I really enjoyed it.
